                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d262">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">832.73/210: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morgan</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rio de Janeiro</hi>
                        </placeName>, [<date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-02-07T17:00:00-03:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 7, 1922—5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>]<lb/>[Received 6:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>13. Department’s 10, February 4, 4 [<hi rend="italic">7</hi>] p.m.<note n="44"
                        xml:id="d262fn44">See footnote 40, <ref target="#pg_518">p.
                        518</ref>.</note> Western Telegraph representative sent me this afternoon
                    copy of petition presented today to the Brazilian Government and addressed to
                    the Director General of Telegraphs in the Ministry of Public Works containing
                    copy of Secretary’s telegram covering resolution of Western relative to
                    preferential and exclusive rights for the operation of all submarine cables in
                    South America.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Morgan</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
